d","4 June 1375":"4 June 1375","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","8 September 1429":"8 September 1429","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","about 1434":"about 1434","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","Gorran, Cornwall, England":"Gorran, Cornwall, England","Madron, Cornwall, England":"Madron, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Treleigh, Cornwall, England":"Treleigh, Cornwall, England","Fentogollon, St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tregarthen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish: habitational name from Trevarthian (either Newlyn East or Saint Hilary, Cornwall). Both placenames derive from Middle Cornish <i>tref</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + a personal name related to Old Welsh <i>Arthgen</i> (Middle Welsh <i>Arthen</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Tregarthen was born in 1390, in Treleigh, Cornwall, England, his father, John William Tregarthen, was 40 and his mother, Maria Jenkin, was 30. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Margaret de Hendower. He died in 1445, in Gorran, Cornwall, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1390–1445":"1390–1445","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1427–1465":"1427–1465","1429–1508":"1429–1508","1434–Female":"1434–Surnud","1350–1444":"1350–1444","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","4 June 1375":"4. juuni 1375","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","8 September 1429":"8. september 1429","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","about 1434":"umbes 1434","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","Gorran, Cornwall, England":"Gorran, Cornwall, England","Madron, Cornwall, England":"Madron, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Treleigh, Cornwall, England":"Treleigh, Cornwall, England","Fentogollon, St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1390–1445":"1390–1445","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1427–1465":"1427–1465","1429–1508":"1429–1508","1434–Female":"1434–Kuollut","1350–1444":"1350–1444","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","4 June 1375":"4. kesäkuuta 1375","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","8 September 1429":"8. syyskuuta 1429","1445":"1445","1434":"1434","1444":"1444","1400":"1400","1465":"1465","about 1434":"noin 1434","1508":"1508","1429":"1429","1427":"1427","Gorran, Cornwall, England":"Gorran, Cornwall, England","Madron, Cornwall, England":"Madron, Cornwall, England","England":"England","Treleigh, Cornwall, England":"Treleigh, Cornwall, England","Fentogollon, St Michael Penkevil, Cornwall, England":"St Michael Penkivel, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"De